BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 85.44 600 Td (Chapter 11: Decluttering with Kids) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 60 585 m 372 585 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 560 Td (Involve children in the process. Let them make decisions about their own items.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 538 Td (Make it fun: play music, set timers, and turn decluttering into a game.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 516 Td (Start with obviously broken or outgrown toys that the child no longer plays with.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 494 Td (Use the one-in-one-out rule: a new toy means an old toy gets donated.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 472 Td (Rotate toys by storing some and swapping them every few weeks for freshness.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 450 Td (Children only play with a fraction of their toys. Fewer options reduce overwhelm.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 428 Td (Donate gently used items together so children see others benefiting.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 406 Td (Do not declutter kids items secretly. They notice and lose trust.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 384 Td (Create easy organization systems children can maintain independently.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 362 Td (Keep toy storage at child height so cleanup is simple and expected.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 340 Td (Art projects can be photographed, displayed temporarily, then recycled.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 318 Td (Children who learn to declutter develop lifelong organizational skills.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 211.2 30 Td (11) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
